TY  - JOUR
T1  - Migration Flows, Their Determinants and the Effects of Return Migration
AU  - Vanderkamp, John
Y1  - 1971/09/01
PY  - 1971
DA  - 1971/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/259812
DO  - 10.1086/259812
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1012
EP  - 1031
VL  - 79
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This paper examines at the theoretical level the distinction among new, return, and autonomous migration flows. This helps to explain the relative magnitudes of observed gross and net migration flows. Return migration has the effect of linking gross migration flows in opposite directions. The income-distance trade-off is strongly affected by the state of the labor market. Thus, not only is the overall level of migration reduced under depressed conditions, but the allocative efficiency of migration is also adversely affected.
AB  - This paper examines at the theoretical level the distinction among new, return, and autonomous migration flows. This helps to explain the relative magnitudes of observed gross and net migration flows. Return migration has the effect of linking gross migration flows in opposite directions. The income-distance trade-off is strongly affected by the state of the labor market. Thus, not only is the overall level of migration reduced under depressed conditions, but the allocative efficiency of migration is also adversely affected.
