T1  - Rates of Amortization of Advertising Expenditures
AU  - Peles, Yoram
Y1  - 1971/09/01
PY  - 1971
DA  - 1971/09/01
N1  - doi: 10.1086/259813
DO  - 10.1086/259813
T2  - Journal of Political Economy
JF  - Journal of Political Economy
SP  - 1032
EP  - 1058
VL  - 79
IS  - 5
PB  - The University of Chicago Press
N2  - This article measures the effect of advertising expenditures on the firm's sales in three industries: beer, cigarettes, and new passenger cars. The annual rate of amortization of advertising expenditures was 40-50 percent for beer and 35-45 percent for cigarettes. The advertising effect is explained in these two nondurable industries by an exponential distributed lag model with two lagged variables--the firm's own advertising and that of its competitors. However, with respect to automobile, advertising increases current sales and this in return has a negative effect on future sales.
AB  - This article measures the effect of advertising expenditures on the firm's sales in three industries: beer, cigarettes, and new passenger cars. The annual rate of amortization of advertising expenditures was 40-50 percent for beer and 35-45 percent for cigarettes. The advertising effect is explained in these two nondurable industries by an exponential distributed lag model with two lagged variables--the firm's own advertising and that of its competitors. However, with respect to automobile, advertising increases current sales and this in return has a negative effect on future sales.
SN  - 0022-3808
M3  - doi: 10.1086/259813
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1086/259813
Y2  - 2024/03/23
